        }
        std::sort(a.begin(), a.end());
        // The median of the first class will be a[n-1]
        // The median of the second class will be a[n]
        // This is because if we pick n elements for the first class,
        // and n elements for the second class,
        // the smallest possible median for the first class (size 1) is a[0].
        // The largest possible median for the first class (size 2n-1) is a[2n-2].
        //
        // Consider the sorted array a_0, a_1, ..., a_{2n-1}.
        // We want to pick k_1 elements for class 1 and k_2 elements for class 2,
        // where k_1 and k_2 are odd, and k_1 + k_2 = 2n.
        //
        // Let's say class 1 has size 2k_A + 1 and class 2 has size 2k_B + 1.
        // The median of class 1 will be its (k_A + 1)-th smallest element.
        // The median of class 2 will be its (k_B + 1)-th smallest element.
        //
        // The optimal strategy is to make the two medians adjacent in the sorted full array.
        // Specifically, the median of one class will be a[n-1] and the median of the other class will be a[n].
        //
        // To achieve this:
        // Class 1: Take a[0], a[1], ..., a[n-1]. This forms a class of size n.
        // If n is odd, then a[n-1] is the median of this class.
        // If n is even, this class size is even, which is not allowed.
        //
        // The problem statement implies that the number of students in each class can be different.
        // The key insight is that to minimize the difference between medians, we should make the medians
        // as close as possible in the sorted list of all students.
        //
        // If we sort all $2n$ skill levels: $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$.
        // We need to pick $2k_1+1$ students for class 1 and $2k_2+1$ students for class 2.
        // $2k_1+1 + 2k_2+1 = 2n \implies 2(k_1+k_2+1) = 2n \implies k_1+k_2+1 = n$.
        //
        // The median of class 1 will be some $a_i$ and the median of class 2 will be some $a_j$.
        // To minimize $|a_i - a_j|$, we should choose $i$ and $j$ to be as close as possible.
        //
        // Consider the elements $a_{n-1}$ and $a_n$.
        // Can we make $a_{n-1}$ the median of one class and $a_n$ the median of the other?
        //
        // Let's try to make $a_{n-1}$ the median of Class 1.
        // This class must have $k_1$ elements smaller than $a_{n-1}$ and $k_1$ elements larger than $a_{n-1}$.
        // The smallest $k_1$ elements are $a_0, \dots, a_{k_1-1}$.
        // So we must have $k_1 \le n-1$.
        //
        // Let's try to make $a_n$ the median of Class 2.
        // This class must have $k_2$ elements smaller than $a_n$ and $k_2$ elements larger than $a_n$.
        // The largest $k_2$ elements are $a_{2n-1}, \dots, a_{2n-k_2}$.
        // So we must have $k_2 \le (2n-1) - n = n-1$.
        //
        // If we pick $a_{n-1}$ as median for class 1, and $a_n$ as median for class 2.
        // Class 1: $a_0, \dots, a_{n-2}$ (n-1 elements), $a_{n-1}$ (1 element), $a_{n+1}, \dots, a_{2n-1}$ (n-1 elements).
        // This is not how it works. We pick students, then sort them.
        //
        // The problem is equivalent to finding two indices $i$ and $j$ such that $a_i$ and $a_j$ can be medians of two valid classes, and $|a_i - a_j|$ is minimized.
        //
        // The crucial observation is that if we sort all $2n$ students, $a_0, a_1, \dots, a_{2n-1}$,
        // the minimum possible difference between the medians of two classes will always be $a_n - a_{n-1}$.
        //
        // To prove this:
        // Let $M_1$ be the median of Class 1 and $M_2$ be the median of Class 2.
        // Suppose $M_1 < M_2$.
        //
        // Class 1 has $2k_1+1$ students. $M_1$ is the $(k_1+1)$-th smallest student in Class 1.
        // Class 2 has $2k_2+1$ students. $M_2$ is the $(k_2+1)$-th smallest student in Class 2.
        //
        // There are at least $k_1$ students in Class 1 with skill $\le M_1$.
        // There are at least $k_2$ students in Class 2 with skill $\le M_2$.
        //
        // Consider the element $a_{n-1}$ from the sorted full list.
        // This element must belong to either Class 1 or Class 2.
        //
        // Case 1: $a_{n-1}$ is in Class 1.
        // Then $M_1 \le a_{n-1}$. (Because $a_{n-1}$ is one of the $2k_1+1$ elements, and $M_1$ is its median).
        //
        // Case 2: $a_{n-1}$ is in Class 2.
